  <p>Every World Cup is sold as the biggest yet. The 2026 edition has an unusually strong claim to the title, and the reason is structural rather than promotional. For the first time, 48 teams will contest the tournament &mdash; up from the 32 that have played every edition since 1998. The match count jumps from 64 to 104. The schedule stretches to 39 days, from June 11 to July 19, across 16 cities in the United States, Mexico, and Canada. More football, by a wide margin, than any World Cup before it. The interesting question for this site is not what that means for the sport. It is what a tournament of that length and density does to a betting market &mdash; and to the people the market can harm.</p>

